\begin_layout Section*
Question 1
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Intuitively, according to the intertemporal approach we would expect consumption
 smoothing, which means
\series bold
 increasing present consumption
\series default
 as a result of a known increase in future income, which would lead to a
 
\series bold
negative current account
\series default
.
 The logic is to add the 
\series bold
present value of the income increase
\series default
 (discounted by 3 periods) to the present (and each subsequent period) consumpti
on.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let us now check this intuition algebraically.
 The balance of payments at period 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 is given by:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
CA_{t}=Y+rB_{t}-C_{t}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
With the expected increase in income three periods from now, the consumption
 is:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
C_{t}=\frac{r}{1+r}\left[1+\frac{1}{1+r}+\frac{1}{(1+r)^{2}}+\sum_{i=3}^{\infty}\frac{1+a}{(1+r)^{i}}\right]Y+rB_{t}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Thus:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
C_{t}=\left(\frac{r}{1+r}\right)\left(\frac{1+r}{r}\right)Y+\left(\frac{r}{1+r}\right)\frac{aY}{(1+r)^{3}}\sum_{i=0}^{\infty}\frac{1}{(1+r)^{i}}+rB_{t}=
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
=Y+\left(\frac{r}{1+r}\right)\frac{aY}{(1+r)^{3}}\frac{1+r}{r}+rB_{t}=Y+\frac{aY}{(1+r)^{3}}+rB_{t}
\]

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Therefore finally:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
CA_{t}=Y+rB_{t}-C_{t}=Y+rB_{t}-Y-\frac{aY}{(1+r)^{3}}-rB_{t}=--\frac{aY}{(1+r)^{3}}<0
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
And indeed the current account is negative.
\end_layout

