\begin_layout Subsection*
(a)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Given positive and equal marginal cost and consumption shocks, the intuition
 suggests that the supply curve shifts 
\series bold
upwards
\series default
 (prices rise), and the demand curve shifts to the 
\series bold
right
\series default
 (positive demand shock introduced by the government - somewhat counterintuitive
, as the prices actually rise, yet the aggregate demand increases).
 The CB will try to fight the shock by increasing the interest rate, thus
 decreasing the shift of the demand curve, but anyway the production level
 will increase
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
(b)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Assuming 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{t}=u_{t}>0$
\end_inset

 and all lagged variables are equal to 0, the model's equations are:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(S)\,\,p_{t}=\kappa x_{t}+u_{t}
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(D)\,\,x_{t}=-i_{t}+u_{t}
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(TR)\,\,i_{t}=\phi_{\pi}p_{t}+\phi_{x}x_{t}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Substitute 
\begin_inset Formula $i_{t}$
\end_inset

 in the demand equation:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
x_{t}=-\phi_{\pi}p_{t}-\phi_{x}x_{t}+u_{t}\Rightarrow p_{t}=-\frac{x_{t}(1+\phi_{x})-u_{t}}{\phi_{\pi}}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Equate supply to demand:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\kappa x_{t}+u_{t}=-\frac{x_{t}(1+\phi_{x})-u_{t}}{\phi_{\pi}}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Using 
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa=0.65$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{\pi}=1.5$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{x}=0.5$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
x_{t}\frac{\kappa\phi_{\pi}+1+\phi_{x}}{\phi_{\pi}}=u_{t}\left(\frac{1-\phi_{\pi}}{\phi_{\pi}}\right)\Rightarrow x_{t}=\frac{u_{t}(1-\phi_{\pi})}{\kappa\phi_{\pi}+1+\phi_{x}}=\frac{u_{t}\cdot(-0.5)}{(+)}<0
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Thus the production
\series bold
 
\series default
actually 
\series bold
decreases 
\series default
(contrary to the intuitive analysis).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Substituting in the demand curve again:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
p_{t}=-\frac{\frac{u_{t}(1-\phi_{\pi})}{\kappa\phi_{\pi}+1+\phi_{x}}(1+\phi_{x})-u_{t}}{\phi_{\pi}}=-\frac{(-)}{(+)}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
and the price level 
\series bold
increases
\series default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The interest rate is given by:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
i_{t}=-\frac{u_{t}(1-\phi_{\pi})}{\kappa\phi_{\pi}+1+\phi_{x}}(1+\phi_{x})+u_{t}+\phi_{x}\frac{u_{t}(1-\phi_{\pi})}{\kappa\phi_{\pi}+1+\phi_{x}}=
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
=\frac{-u_{t}(1-\phi_{\pi})(1+\phi_{x})+u_{t}(\kappa\phi_{\pi}+1+\phi_{x})+\phi_{x}u_{t}(1-\phi_{\pi})}{\kappa\phi_{\pi}+1+\phi_{x}}>0
\]

\end_inset

and it 
\series bold
increases
\series default
 as well.
\end_layout

