\begin_layout Subsection*
(a) 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Intuitively, 
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa=0$
\end_inset

 means that the prices are constant in the model (given the exogenous variables
 are fixed), and do not change as function of demand.
 It means that the supply curve is a horizontal line (unlike the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

normal
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 open economy model, where it is an upward sloping curve).
 The demand curve is a downward sloping curve.
 A marginal cost shock shifts the supply curve upwards, which leads to a
 price increase and production decrease (assuming no CB intervention).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Then the CB tries to smoothen the shock.
 It is hard to determine (without performing the numerical calculations)
 the exact effect on the interest rate, because the price level and the
 production output have opposite effects on it, and they both increase.
 We can assume it will probably increase by CB intervention, yet the effect
 on the exchange rate is hard to tell as well - because the prices level
 and the interest rate have opposite effects on it.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
(b)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Assuming 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{t}>0$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa=0$
\end_inset

 and all lagged variables are equal to 0, the model's equations are:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(S)\,\,p_{t}=u_{t}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Which means that the whole marginal cost shock is fully translated to a
 
\series bold
price increase
\series default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(D)\,\,p_{t}=-\frac{1}{\vartheta}x_{t}-\frac{1}{\vartheta}i_{t}+e_{t}
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(UIP)\,\,e_{t}=p_{t}-i_{t}
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(TR)\,\,i_{t}=\phi_{\pi}p_{t}+\phi_{x}x_{t}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Substitute 
\begin_inset Formula $e_{t}$
\end_inset

 in the demand equation:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
p_{t}=-\frac{1}{\vartheta}x_{t}-\frac{1}{\vartheta}i_{t}+p_{t}-i_{t}\Rightarrow x_{t}=-(1+\vartheta)i_{t}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Substitute 
\begin_inset Formula $i_{t}$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
x_{t}=-(1+\vartheta)(\phi_{\pi}p_{t}+\phi_{x}x_{t})\Rightarrow p_{t}=-\frac{1+(1+\vartheta)\phi_{x}}{(1+\vartheta)\phi_{\pi}}x_{t}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The coefficient is negative, thus 
\series bold
the production decreases
\series default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Equate supply and demand:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
u_{t}=-\frac{1+(1+\vartheta)\phi_{x}}{(1+\vartheta)\phi_{\pi}}x_{t}\Rightarrow x_{t}=-\frac{(1+\vartheta)\phi_{\pi}u_{t}}{1+(1+\vartheta)\phi_{x}}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Substitute 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 to Taylor rule in order to find the interest rate:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
i_{t}=\phi_{\pi}u_{t}-\phi_{x}\frac{(1+\vartheta)\phi_{\pi}u_{t}}{1+(1+\vartheta)\phi_{x}}=\frac{\phi_{\pi}u_{t}}{1+(1+\vartheta)\phi_{x}}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Using 
\begin_inset Formula $\vartheta=0.3$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{\pi}=1.5$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{x}=0.5$
\end_inset

, we conclude that the 
\series bold
interest rate will increase
\series default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Finally, the 
\series bold
exchange rate
\series default
 
\series bold
increases
\series default
 as well:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
e_{t}=p_{t}-i_{t}=u_{t}-\frac{\phi_{\pi}u_{t}}{1+(1+\vartheta)\phi_{x}}=\frac{u_{t}[1+(1+\vartheta)\phi_{x}-\phi_{\pi}]}{1+(1+\vartheta)\phi_{x}}=\frac{u_{t}\cdot(1+1.3\cdot0.5-1.5)}{(+)}>0
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

